In `apps/desktop/src-tauri/src/fs_utils.rs`, the `cleanup_stale_tmp_files` function currently matches stale temp files using `path.extension().map_or(false, |ext| ext == "tmp")`. However, `atomic_write` writes to paths created via `path.with_extension("json.tmp")`, producing filenames like `state.json.tmp`. `Path::extension()` on `state.json.tmp` returns `"json.tmp"` (not `"tmp"`), so the cleanup never matches the files it was written to clean. After a crash mid-write, `state.json.tmp` accumulates indefinitely.

Fix: replace the extension-based check on line 237 with a suffix-on-filename check, mirroring the watcher's filter at `watcher.rs:172` which uses `name.ends_with(".tmp")`:

```rust
} else if path.file_name().and_then(|n| n.to_str()).map_or(false, |n| n.ends_with(".tmp")) {
```

This is the only code change. The `atomic_write` `with_extension("json.tmp")` call is intentionally left alone — the filename pattern stays the same; only the cleanup matcher is fixed.
